Probably the simpliest way to explain this is the moment of instantiation. When you write:

    regClass instance;

then the compiler is unable to deduce the `T` type of the embedded template `templClass&lt;T&gt;` class. `templClass` alone by itself is not a complete type.

Therefore you have two options:

 1. Specify the type directly inside the `regClass` class definition:

```
    class regClass
    {
    public:
        regClass()
        {
            // constructor for other members
        }
        int var;
        templClass&lt;int&gt; templClass_;
        // [...]
    };
```
That way you can write `regClass instance;`, but the embedded object type will always be of type `templClass&lt;int&gt;`.

 2. Make the external class a templated class:
```
    template &lt;class T&gt;
    class regClass
    {
    public:
        regClass()
        {
            // constructor for other members
        }
        int var;
        templClass&lt;T&gt; templClass_;
        // [...]
    };
```
This way you can decide the type at the moment of instantiation, e.g. `regClass&lt;std::string&gt; instance;`.

